mantebea <- import(here("data", "cancer_data.csv"))
mantebea <- mantebea %>%
                  mutate(
                         gender = factor (gender) %>%
                                 fct_recode ("Male" = "0",
                                             "Female" = "1") %>%
                                 ff_label ("Gender") %>%
                         fct_relevel ("Male", "Female"),
                         
                         smoking = factor (smoking) %>%
                                  fct_recode ("Never smoked" = "0",
                                              "Light smoker" = "1",
                                              "Heavy smoker" = "2") %>%
                                  ff_label ("Smoking") %>%
                         fct_relevel ("Never smoked", "Light smoker", "Heavy smoker") ,
                         
                         exercise = factor (exercise) %>%
                                   fct_recode ("Sedentary" = "0",
                                               "Active" = "1",
                                               "Very active" = "2") %>%
                                   ff_label ("Exercise") %>%
                         fct_relevel ("Sedentary", "Active", "Very active"),
                         
                         cancer = factor (cancer) %>%
                                 fct_recode ("Yes" = "0",
                                             "No" = "1") %>%
                                 ff_label ("Cancer") %>%
                         fct_relevel ("Yes", "No"),
                         
                         age = age %>%
                           ff_label ("Age"),
                         
                         patient_id = patient_id %>%
                           ff_label ("Patient ID"),
                         
                         bmi = bmi %>%
                           ff_label ("BMI")
                  )   
bmi_cat<-
        ifelse (mantebea$bmi <18.5, "Underweight",
                ifelse (mantebea$bmi >=18.5 & mantebea$bmi <=24.9, "Normal",
                        ifelse (mantebea$bmi >=25 & mantebea$bmi <=29.9, "Overweight",
                                ifelse (mantebea$bmi >30, "Obese", NA))))
mantebea$bmi_cat <- bmi_cat
mantebea <- mantebea %>%
                  mutate(
                    bmi_cat = factor (bmi_cat) %>%
                             ff_label ("BMI Cat") %>%
                             fct_relevel ("Underweight", "Normal", "Overweight", "Obese")
                  )

#creating scatterplot
ggplot(mantebea, aes(x=age, y=bmi, color=factor(gender))) +geom_point()

## In the chunk below, I changed the default point shape of the plot from 16 to 8. 
ggplot(mantebea, aes(x=age, y=bmi, color=factor(gender))) +geom_point(shape = 8)

## Faceting was introduced in this function. As such, the same plot produced in the previous function was further divided or split into subgroups based on their respective bmi categories. From observation. more females fell under the overweight section whiles more males were classified as normal.
ggplot(mantebea, aes(x=age, y=bmi, color=factor(gender))) +
  geom_point(shape = 8) +
  facet_wrap(~bmi_cat)

## The chunk below has also been split into subgroups (faceting). A condition was however provided in this function, that is; people with patient_id number below 50. Hence, the False plot includes people with patient id above or greater than 50 whiles the True plot includes people with patient id below or less than 50. More people fell under the true plot from observation.
ggplot(mantebea, aes(x=age, y=bmi, color=factor(gender))) +
  geom_point(shape = 8) +
  facet_wrap(~patient_id < 50)

## For this next function, Im going to change the background theme of the plots above to give it a different look. This was just done for practice.
ggplot(mantebea, aes(x=age, y=bmi, color=factor(gender))) +
  geom_point(shape = 8) +
  facet_wrap(~bmi_cat) +
  theme_dark()

## I'm going to convert the plot from a scatter plot into a bubble plot in this next function by including a 'size' aesthetic. ## The above function worked, however because of the shape of the points, we can't really see the bubbles. So I'm going to change the point shape in the next function. I believe the points are transparent and hollow enough so there will be no need to include the aesthetic "alpha".
ggplot(mantebea, aes(x=age, y=bmi, color=factor(exercise), size = gender)) +

## For this next function, I'm going to create a line plot (second plot for the assignment) by including the 'group' aesthetic. I also changed the theme to a white background. So it didn't work the first time because each group (Patient id) consists of only one observation. I guess it's either i change the group or i remove the faceting. Let's try both and see. Okay, so removing the faceting didn't change anything. It still gave me the same problem. So let's change the group rathe. Eventually changing the group helped but then making the faceting variable the same as the color factor gave absolutely no problem.
